{"parentUuid":"041059cb-2ea8-44ad-9ed1-9d239c2ec989","isSidechain":false,"promptId":"cb69b170-7632-4e04-b3d8-e25a03af4602","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01N5n9VfahzrXzYetS7BJpkR","type":"tool_result","content":"195\t`--exclude-ref-prefix` subtracts from auto-discovery (branches, tags, and\n196\t`--all-refs` namespaces) and from prune scope, so excluded refs are left\n197\talone entirely: not pulled from source, not pushed to target, not pruned\n198\tfrom target. Explicit `--map` entries are not subject to this filter.\n199\t\n200\t`replicate --all-refs` broadens the same scope but does NOT enable\n201\tbest-effort. Replicate's contract is \"target refs match source\"; downgrading\n202\trejected refs to warnings would let partial mirrors exit successfully,\n203\twhich contradicts the command. Use `sync --all-refs` if you want\n204\tbest-effort completeness against hostile targets.\n205\t\n206\t`sync --all-refs` blocks updates to non-branch refs (notes, pulls, custom\n207\tnamespaces) by default — those refs don't generally form fast-forward\n208\tchains, so the same `--force` opt-in that retargets tags is required to\n209\tupdate them. `replicate` doesn't run that check; its overwrite contract\n210\tcovers other-kind refs without `--force`.\n211\t\n212\t`SyncPolicy.BestEffort` is independent of scope and can be set without\n213\t`AllRefs` if a library caller wants per-ref warn semantics on a narrower\n214\tscope.\n215\t\n216\tForce source-side protocol v2:\n217\t\n218\t```bash\n219\tgit-sync sync \\\n220\t  --protocol v2 \\\n221\t  <source-url> \\\n222\t  <target-url>\n223\t```\n224\t\n225\t## HEAD / Default Branch\n226\t\n227\tgit-sync surfaces the source's symref HEAD target — the source's default\n228\tbranch — in result output:\n229\t\n230\t- JSON: `execution.sourceHead` (sync / plan / replicate / bootstrap); `sourceHead` (probe).\n231\t- Human: a `source-head: <ref>` line.\n232\t\n233\t```\n234\t$ git-sync probe --json <source-url> | jq .sourceHead\n235\t\"refs/heads/main\"\n236\t```\n237\t\n238\t**Bootstrap pushes the source HEAD's branch first.** When initializating a new \n239\trepository, the default branch is based on the first push to a fresh repo (GitHub, GitLab,\n240\tothers), this makes the mirror's default branch match the source\n241\twithout any manual step. No flag needed — the ordering is always applied.\n242\t\n243\tgit's wire protocol has no command for updating a remote symref, so for\n244\thosts that *don't* infer the default from first-push (raw bare repos,\n245\tsome self-hosted setups), the default branch has to be set out of band:\n246\t\n247\t1. **Match the default at init time** — `git init --bare --initial-branch=<source-default>` on the target before the first sync.\n248\t2. **Set HEAD post-sync** — `git symbolic-ref HEAD refs/heads/<source-default>` on the bare repo, or the host's API/UI (GitHub `PATCH /repos/{owner}/{repo}` with `default_branch`; GitLab `PUT /projects/:id` with `default_branch`).\n249\t\n250\t## JSON Output\n251\t\n252\tAdd `--json` to any command to emit machine-readable output instead of the default text format.\n253\t\n254\tThe JSON interface is stable:\n255\t\n256\t- keys use `camelCase`\n257\t- refs and hashes are serialized as strings, not raw byte arrays\n258\t- top-level keys include `plans`, `pushed`, `skipped`, `blocked`, `deleted`, `warned`, `dryRun`, `protocol`, and `stats`, plus `relay`, `relayMode`, `relayReason`, `batching`, `batchCount`, `plannedBatchCount`, and `tempRefs`\n259\t- each item in `plans` includes stable string fields such as `branch`, `sourceRef`, `targetRef`, `sourceHash`, `targetHash`, `kind`, `action`, and `reason`\n260\t- `execution.sourceHead` (sync/plan/replicate/bootstrap) and `sourceHead` (probe) carry the source's symref HEAD target when advertised\n261\t\n262\t## Auth\n263\t\n264\tFor GitHub and similar providers, use basic auth with a token as the password.\n265\t\n266\tAuth is resolved in this order:\n267\t\n268\t- explicit CLI flags\n269\t- `GITSYNC_*` environment variables\n270\t- local `git credential fill` helper lookup for `http` and `https` remotes\n271\t- anonymous access\n272\t\n273\tRelevant variables:\n274\t\n275\t- `GITSYNC_SOURCE_TOKEN`\n276\t- `GITSYNC_TARGET_TOKEN`\n277\t- `GITSYNC_SOURCE_USERNAME` default: `git`\n278\t- `GITSYNC_TARGET_USERNAME` default: `git`\n279\t\n280\tBearer auth is also available:\n281\t\n282\t- `GITSYNC_SOURCE_BEARER_TOKEN`\n283\t- `GITSYNC_TARGET_BEARER_TOKEN`\n284\t\n285\tThat means local testing against a dummy GitHub repo can reuse your regular Git credential helper setup without passing tokens on every command.\n286\t\n287\t## Protocol Notes\n288\t\n289\t- Source-side discovery and fetch can use protocol v2 when supported. Push stays on the existing v1 `receive-pack` path. `--protocol auto` tries v2 first and falls back to v1. `--protocol v2` requires the source to negotiate v2.\n290\t- Source fetch advertises current target tip hashes as `have`, so reruns download less when source and target already share history.\n291\t- Branches are updated only when the target tip is an ancestor of the source tip, unless `--force` is set. Tags are immutable by default. Retargeting an existing tag requires `--force`. With `--prune`, managed target refs that are absent on source are deleted.\n292\t- If `sync` finds blocked refs, it exits non-zero before pushing anything.\n293\t- `--stats` adds per-service request, byte, want, have, and command counters to the output.\n294\t\n295\tFor the deeper protocol-level walkthrough (smart HTTP, pkt-line, capability negotiation, sideband stripping, relay framing), see [protocol.md](protocol.md).\n296\t"}]},"uuid":"cb00470e-7316-4d79-a5ed-98aa1db53d55","timestamp":"2026-05-12T21:20:29.170Z","toolUseResult":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/git-sync/docs/usage.md","content":"`--exclude-ref-prefix` subtracts from auto-discovery (branches, tags, and\n`--all-refs` namespaces) and from prune scope, so excluded refs are left\nalone entirely: not pulled from source, not pushed to target, not pruned\nfrom target. Explicit `--map` entries are not subject to this filter.\n\n`replicate --all-refs` broadens the same scope but does NOT enable\nbest-effort. Replicate's contract is \"target refs match source\"; downgrading\nrejected refs to warnings would let partial mirrors exit successfully,\nwhich contradicts the command. Use `sync --all-refs` if you want\nbest-effort completeness against hostile targets.\n\n`sync --all-refs` blocks updates to non-branch refs (notes, pulls, custom\nnamespaces) by default — those refs don't generally form fast-forward\nchains, so the same `--force` opt-in that retargets tags is required to\nupdate them. `replicate` doesn't run that check; its overwrite contract\ncovers other-kind refs without `--force`.\n\n`SyncPolicy.BestEffort` is independent of scope and can be set without\n`AllRefs` if a library caller wants per-ref warn semantics on a narrower\nscope.\n\nForce source-side protocol v2:\n\n```bash\ngit-sync sync \\\n  --protocol v2 \\\n  <source-url> \\\n  <target-url>\n```\n\n## HEAD / Default Branch\n\ngit-sync surfaces the source's symref HEAD target — the source's default\nbranch — in result output:\n\n- JSON: `execution.sourceHead` (sync / plan / replicate / bootstrap); `sourceHead` (probe).\n- Human: a `source-head: <ref>` line.\n\n```\n$ git-sync probe --json <source-url> | jq .sourceHead\n\"refs/heads/main\"\n```\n\n**Bootstrap pushes the source HEAD's branch first.** When initializating a new \nrepository, the default branch is based on the first push to a fresh repo (GitHub, GitLab,\nothers), this makes the mirror's default branch match the source\nwithout any manual step. No flag needed — the ordering is always applied.\n\ngit's wire protocol has no command for updating a remote symref, so for\nhosts that *don't* infer the default from first-push (raw bare repos,\nsome self-hosted setups), the default branch has to be set out of band:\n\n1. **Match the default at init time** — `git init --bare --initial-branch=<source-default>` on the target before the first sync.\n2. **Set HEAD post-sync** — `git symbolic-ref HEAD refs/heads/<source-default>` on the bare repo, or the host's API/UI (GitHub `PATCH /repos/{owner}/{repo}` with `default_branch`; GitLab `PUT /projects/:id` with `default_branch`).\n\n## JSON Output\n\nAdd `--json` to any command to emit machine-readable output instead of the default text format.\n\nThe JSON interface is stable:\n\n- keys use `camelCase`\n- refs and hashes are serialized as strings, not raw byte arrays\n- top-level keys include `plans`, `pushed`, `skipped`, `blocked`, `deleted`, `warned`, `dryRun`, `protocol`, and `stats`, plus `relay`, `relayMode`, `relayReason`, `batching`, `batchCount`, `plannedBatchCount`, and `tempRefs`\n- each item in `plans` includes stable string fields such as `branch`, `sourceRef`, `targetRef`, `sourceHash`, `targetHash`, `kind`, `action`, and `reason`\n- `execution.sourceHead` (sync/plan/replicate/bootstrap) and `sourceHead` (probe) carry the source's symref HEAD target when advertised\n\n## Auth\n\nFor GitHub and similar providers, use basic auth with a token as the password.\n\nAuth is resolved in this order:\n\n- explicit CLI flags\n- `GITSYNC_*` environment variables\n- local `git credential fill` helper lookup for `http` and `https` remotes\n- anonymous access\n\nRelevant variables:\n\n- `GITSYNC_SOURCE_TOKEN`\n- `GITSYNC_TARGET_TOKEN`\n- `GITSYNC_SOURCE_USERNAME` default: `git`\n- `GITSYNC_TARGET_USERNAME` default: `git`\n\nBearer auth is also available:\n\n- `GITSYNC_SOURCE_BEARER_TOKEN`\n- `GITSYNC_TARGET_BEARER_TOKEN`\n\nThat means local testing against a dummy GitHub repo can reuse your regular Git credential helper setup without passing tokens on every command.\n\n## Protocol Notes\n\n- Source-side discovery and fetch can use protocol v2 when supported. Push stays on the existing v1 `receive-pack` path. `--protocol auto` tries v2 first and falls back to v1. `--protocol v2` requires the source to negotiate v2.\n- Source fetch advertises current target tip hashes as `have`, so reruns download less when source and target already share history.\n- Branches are updated only when the target tip is an ancestor of the source tip, unless `--force` is set. Tags are immutable by default. Retargeting an existing tag requires `--force`. With `--prune`, managed target refs that are absent on source are deleted.\n- If `sync` finds blocked refs, it exits non-zero before pushing anything.\n- `--stats` adds per-service request, byte, want, have, and command counters to the output.\n\nFor the deeper protocol-level walkthrough (smart HTTP, pkt-line, capability negotiation, sideband stripping, relay framing), see [protocol.md](protocol.md).\n","numLines":102,"startLine":195,"totalLines":296}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"041059cb-2ea8-44ad-9ed1-9d239c2ec989","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/git-sync","sessionId":"aefcb05b-206d-434a-94bf-d11991a74a0a","version":"2.1.129","gitBranch":"main"}
